&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Herbert Yang</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 27 Jun 2013 10:33:00 -0700</pubDate><guid>tag:guizishanren.com,2013-06-27:swan-song-by-the-spillovers/</guid><category>spillovers</category><category>coassf</category></item><item><title>COASSF#56 - How To Make A Star</title><link>http://guizishanren.com/how-to-make-a-star/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;From a recent project in my favorite course of the quarter: OB388
Leadership in Entertainment Business, my group researched and analyzed
the success of K-Pop. During this exhilarating intellectual process, I
came up with this graph that illustrates how to find the optimal path of
nurturing a star from scratch. The horizontal dimension, from low to
high, represents the technical difficulty of acquiring certain skills
(which are also the cultural products those stars will eventually
produce) for a star in an entertainment business. The vertical
dimension, from low to high, represents  the cultural barrier those
cultural products will encounter when they are delivered to a foreign
culture (like from South Korea to America).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="../../../../images/Star-Making.png" width="800px" alt="How to make a star"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That's why for K-Pop stars, they all start with dancing and singing.
It's called Audiovisuality. It gets more difficult after that.&lt;/p&gt;</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Herbert Yang</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 05 Jun 2013 17:01:00 -0700</pubDate><guid>tag:guizishanren.com,2013-06-05:how-to-make-a-star/</guid><category>coassf</category></item><item><title>COASSF#55 - GCBC Talk - Stay Full Stay Smart</title><link>http://guizishanren.com/stay-full-stay-smart/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;GCBC Talk Series: &lt;em&gt;Stay Full, Stay Smart&lt;/em&gt;, by Herbert Yang&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Date:       May 29, Wednesday&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Time:           9-10pm&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Venue:          Schwab Ferguson Lounge&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Crunching Tiger, Hidden Dragon&lt;/em&gt; - how was the Gangnam Style Flash
Mob born into GSB on Oct 12, 2012?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Wedding Banquet&lt;/em&gt; - how to manage a rock band?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Hulk&lt;/em&gt; - a career from CFO to movie producer&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Sense and Sensibility&lt;/em&gt; - how to tell stories with your pictures?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Eat Drink Man Woman&lt;/em&gt; - what are the drivers of your life&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Pushing Hands&lt;/em&gt; - How to manage career transition?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ride with the Devil&lt;/em&gt; - What do you bring to the table, as a
leader?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Brokeback Mountain&lt;/em&gt; - What are the different goals in GSB, in
Stanford, in any community&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Lust, Caution&lt;/em&gt; - What exactly does a CFO do?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Life of Pi&lt;/em&gt; - Reflections of a sea turtle&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Days of Being Wild&lt;/em&gt; - The good, the Bad, the Ugly of running
startups in Beijing&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It'll be a casual talk. Given the crazy academic schedule this week, I
don't expect more than 10-15 people to show up. I'll pick up some topics
that the audience are most interested in, during this prolonged late
coffee break. I'll have Ang Lee to take care of the business part, and
maybe save Wong Kar Wai for the non-business part, for later.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Evidently, I was too bored.&lt;/p&gt;</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Herbert Yang</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 28 May 2013 00:19:00 -0700</pubDate><guid>tag:guizishanren.com,2013-05-28:stay-full-stay-smart/</guid><category>coassf</category></item><item><title>COASSF#54 - The Spillovers Live! at Stanford Coho Cafe</title><link>http://guizishanren.com/rock-out-stanford-coho/</link><description>&lt;p&gt;When you see Sloans dancing on the table in usually low-key Stanford
Coho cafe, you know this party is a riot. This is the TGIF that ends all
other TGIFs. This is The-Moment-Of-The-Year for Sloan Fellow Class of
2013 of Stanford Graduate Business School. Thank you, my bandmates of
Sloan's house band The Spillovers, we did it!&lt;/p&gt;
